	affiliations = {Department of ECE, School of Electrical and Electronics, Sathyabama Institute of Science and Technology, Chennai, 600119, India; Department of Networking and Communications, School of Computing, Faculty of Engineering and Technology, SRM Institute of Science and Technology, Kattankulathur, Chennai, 603203, India; E & CE department, Dr. HN National College of Engg, Jayanagar, Bangalore, 560070, India; Dept. of Computer Science and Engineering, Lakireddy Bali Reddy College of Engineering (Autonomous), Mylavaram, NTR Dt, Andhra Pradesh, 521230, India; Department of ECE, Aditya University, Surampalem, India; Department of Computer Science and Engineering, Koneru Lakshmaiah Education Foundation, Vaddeswaram, A.P, Guntur, 522302, India; Department of Computer Science and Engineering, E.G.S. Pillay Engineering College, Nagapattinam, India; Computer Science & Engineering, Applied College, Dhahran Al Janoub Campus, King Khalid University, Abha, Saudi Arabia},
	abstract = {As urban waterscapes face mounting pressures from climate change and rapid urbanization, innovative frameworks are needed to ensure resilience, fairness, and sustainability. This paper introduces the Fodba architecture for autonomous and adaptive water resource management in future sustainable cities, built upon FDTB principles. The system integrates real-time IoT sensing with federated machine learning at the edge, enabling privacy-preserving collaboration among intermediate gateways without sharing raw customer data. All data is maintained on a blockchain substrate, ensuring protection without the need for censorship, revocation, or temporal traceability, while smart contracts enforce equitable resource allocation policies. Central to the architecture is a digital twin of the water system, continuously updated with sensor telemetry and blockchain-anchored events. This twin allows proactive anticipation of bursts and resource depletion, resilience stress-testing, and self-organized water distribution reformation. We validated Fodba in AquaCity-25, an emulated smart city with 10,000 IoT water sensors, 5000 households with Bitcoin wallets, and 25 blockchain validator nodes. Results show a 27.6 % reduction in non-revenue water and a 14.3 % improvement in demand prediction accuracy over baseline LSTM models. Blockchain transaction finality is achieved within 150 ms at p95 latency. Fairness indices remain above 0.92 under variable demand, while federated learning reduces raw data transmissions by 61 %, preserving privacy and energy efficiency. By uniting blockchain, federated intelligence, and digital-twin simulation, Fodba offers a blueprint for autonomous, resilient, and ethical urban water infrastructures. The architecture demonstrates a model for transparent governance, climate-ready utilities, and digitally resilient smart cities. © 2026},
