	abstract = {With the advancement of urban transformation and sustainable development, the Adaptive Reuse of Industrial Heritage Buildings (ARIHB) has become a global focus in research and practice. However, existing methodological systems remain fragmented and lack systematic evaluation. Following the PICOS and PRISMA procedures, this study screened 57 core English-language articles from 1,055 retrieved records and classified the methodologies into five categories: Decision-Making Tools, Design and Planning Methods, Analytical Methods, Case Study Methods, and Evaluation Methods. The findings show that ARIHB methodologies exhibit features of diversification, interdisciplinary integration, and technology-driven development, with notable progress in decision support, data-driven design, and digital twin simulations. Five key limitations were identified: lack of cross-scale integration frameworks, limited depth of digital technology application, insufficient cross-cultural comparison, absence of long-term performance evaluation, and inadequate incorporation of climate change perspectives. Finally, this study proposes a future research agenda, emphasizing the need to build integrated methodological systems that are both context-sensitive and operational, in order to address the intersecting challenges of heritage conservation, urban renewal, and climate resilience. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.},
