	doi = {10.3992/jgb.21.1.367},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105029719070&doi=10.3992%2Fjgb.21.1.367&partnerID=40&md5=fd3a4eb3c2d905c46b57646d667cfc8c},
	affiliations = {College of Art and Design, Shanghai Lida College, 1788 Cheting Highway, Songjiang District, Shanghai, China; College of Fashion and Design, Donghua University, Shanghai, 20051, China; Faculty of Education, Shinawatra University, Pathum Thani, 12160, Thailand; College of Fine Arts, Fujian Normal University, Qishan Campus, No. 18, Middle Wulong River Avenue, Shangjie Town, Minhou County, Fujian Province, Fuzhou City, 350117, China},
	abstract = {The circular economy (CE) paradigm, with its focus on sustainability and resource efficiency, is increasingly being recognized for its applicability to cultural heritage management. This study bridges the research gap by systematically analyzing 1015 articles from the Web of Science database, revealing the potential of CE principles to enhance the longevity of heritage assets and minimize resource use, particu-larly through adaptive reuse. The policy integration of cultural heritage within the “Circular City” framework underscores its role in sustainable urban development. Methodologically, adaptive reuse and life-cycle assessment (LCA) are identified as pivotal for assessing environmental and economic benefits within a CE framework. The study also advocates for integrated evaluation systems, such as multi-criteria decision analysis, to navigate the complex objectives of sustainable heritage manage-ment. Furthermore, the thematic evolution analysis revealed a clear progression in the research focus from broad concepts such as “landscape” to specific entities such as “buildings,” and a paradigm shift from foundational explorations to a more sys-tematic, policy-driven, and methodologically mature stage. Future research is urged to employ tools like LCA, Life Cycle Costing (LCC), and Social LCA (S-LCA) for a holistic evaluation of cultural heritage projects, fostering interdisciplinary collabo-ration and new governance models that leverage cultural heritage as a catalyst for circular innovation. Stakeholder engagement is emphasized to integrate diverse perspectives and enable effective decision-making, while the use of emerging technolo-gies, such as digital twins and historical building information modeling, is suggested to preserve cultural heritage sites. © 2026, College Publishing. All rights reserved.},
	author_keywords = {adaptive reuse; circular cities; circular economy; cultural heritage; life cycle assessment; sustainable development},
